1091
01:38:21,840 --> 01:38:29,400
then you have all of the data. If you're sharing 
ideas, you still have all of the ideas. And the  

1092
01:38:29,400 --> 01:38:34,280
mistake that most people do when they're preparing 
a talk, a presentation, an all hands a meeting,  

1093
01:38:34,280 --> 01:38:41,160
whatever it is we tend to focus more on what 
we want to say than what we want our audience  

1094
01:38:41,160 --> 01:38:47,800
to remember. So the mindset shift here is stop 
focusing as much on what you want to say and focus  

1095
01:38:47,800 --> 01:38:53,440
more on what you want your audience to remember.
What we found out is if you think about  

1096
01:38:54,000 --> 01:38:59,520
your last all hands, the last big meeting, 
the last talk you saw on YouTube or in person,  

1097
01:38:59,520 --> 01:39:07,520
you probably don't remember much. In fact, I wager 
you might only remember one thing from that talk.  

1098
01:39:07,520 --> 01:39:14,080
And that's what this is all based on. We call it 
the bow and arrow technique because we think you  

1099
01:39:14,080 --> 01:39:20,680
can only remember one thing out of a talk and that 
it's very powerful to go through that framework or  

1100
01:39:20,680 --> 01:39:25,200
that kind of thinking when you're building a 
talk. And the one thing is your arrow. And so  

1101
01:39:25,200 --> 01:39:32,600
when you have that one thing to me I say it's 
literally a single sentence that is the only  

1102
01:39:32,600 --> 01:39:37,440
sentence people would remember if they left your 
talk. Would you be satisfied with that sentence? 

1103
01:39:37,440 --> 01:39:42,400
It takes some times to get to a good one, but 
if you have a good one, it unlocks everything.  

1104
01:39:42,400 --> 01:39:45,920
It's like you're having a north star or a 
compass in your pocket. You can always pull  

1105
01:39:45,920 --> 01:39:51,720
it out. You always know where you're going. It 
gives you a lot of clarity. It's also giving  

1106
01:39:51,720 --> 01:39:56,480
a lot of clarity to your audience obviously.
But you can't just throw an arrow at somebody's  

1107
01:39:56,480 --> 01:40:04,000
face. You need to notch it in the bow and pull 
the bow back. And so to pull the bow back, you  

1108
01:40:04,000 --> 01:40:13,640
need to add in weight to that sentence. And that 
often comes in the form of an interesting anecdote  

1109
01:40:13,640 --> 01:40:20,160
or a data point that's going to support that or 
a story that's going to add emotion or illustrate  

1110
01:40:20,160 --> 01:40:28,480
it. So you want to find ways in which you can give 
weight or pull back the bow so that your arrow has  

1111
01:40:28,480 --> 01:40:38,000
that much more impact. So usually the process of 
clarifying what your arrow is is a back and forth  

1112
01:40:38,000 --> 01:40:44,760
between the bow and the arrows. So if you're going 
down the accordion method after the first one you  

1113
01:40:44,760 --> 01:40:49,760
might write or before the first one, you might 
write a tentative arrow, "Here's my one thing",  

1114
01:40:49,760 --> 01:40:55,340
and then the next one you say, "Okay, actually 
my one thing might be a refined version of that." 

1115
01:40:55,340 --> 01:41:01,000
And so you might rewrite it a little bit and 
then you might tentatively put in what you  

1116
01:41:01,000 --> 01:41:07,560
think the bow is. "I like the anecdote I used 
here. I like this data point that I thought was  

1117
01:41:07,560 --> 01:41:11,840
powerful and maybe I can end on this story or 
this call to action." Then you'll put that in  

1118
01:41:11,840 --> 01:41:16,960
and then you go back in and you give that a try 
and that's starting to simplify in your mind. 

1119
01:41:16,960 --> 01:41:22,680
And as you go, usually one informs the other. By 
the time you finish the accordion for example,  

1120
01:41:22,680 --> 01:41:28,480
you should have a very clear arrow and those 
clear bookmarks, which is the bow. But really  

1121
01:41:28,480 --> 01:41:34,960
the thing to remember with the bow and arrow, if 
you can only remember one thing, is switch your  

1122
01:41:34,960 --> 01:41:42,520
mindset from what I want to say to what I want 
people to remember and limit whatever that is  

1123
01:41:42,520 --> 01:41:48,640
you want them to remember as much as possible 
and that's going to give you extreme clarity.

1124
01:41:48,640 --> 01:41:53,440
That is really helpful. I'm preparing my 
talk for the summit, and so I'm going to  

1125
01:41:53,440 --> 01:41:59,160
use both of these exercises and what I 
take away from this last piece is as much  

1126
01:41:59,160 --> 01:42:02,000
as you may want to say a lot of things, 
really all someone's going to remember,  

1127
01:42:02,000 --> 01:42:06,440
as you said is one thing, if anything, but 
hopefully they remember that one thing. 

1128
01:42:06,440 --> 01:42:11,840
So it's essentially what's the one thing you want 
people to remember and then what are the pieces of  

1129
01:42:11,840 --> 01:42:16,760
support that will convince them that that's right 
and that's something that'll stick with them?

1130
01:42:16,760 --> 01:42:23,280
Exactly. And again, similar to the accordion 
method, this works in the macro and the micro.  

1131
01:42:23,280 --> 01:42:28,920
So if you have a talk where you're using 
slides, use it for the whole talk. But  

1132
01:42:28,920 --> 01:42:36,240
then for every single slide, ask yourself 
what is my one thing? And you might have  

1133
01:42:36,240 --> 01:42:40,640
some support there as well, but if you 
don't have a one thing for each slide,  

1134
01:42:40,640 --> 01:42:44,520
either the slide shouldn't exist 
or it should be multiple slides. 

1135
01:42:45,080 --> 01:42:51,120
The symptom of not having a one thing is 
usually having a slide that says way too  

1136
01:42:51,120 --> 01:42:55,240
many things. I don't know what data point I 
want you to remember, so I'm going to put all  

1137
01:42:55,240 --> 01:42:59,680
of it on that slide. I'm not sure which piece 
of information is more important. So I'm going  

1138
01:42:59,680 --> 01:43:04,240
to write down all of my thoughts and I'm going 
to go through all of them or hope that you go  

1139
01:43:04,240 --> 01:43:09,400
through all of them and extract what you think 
is interesting. But the reality is people are  

1140
01:43:09,400 --> 01:43:15,960
just going to zone out if you do that. So if 
you do that slide by slide, you're going to  

1141
01:43:15,960 --> 01:43:21,520
gain incredible clarity and again, you're going 
to need less preparation and less memorization.

1142
01:43:21,520 --> 01:43:26,600
And to build on that, a pro-tip is to make that 
title of that slide exactly that one thing you  

1143
01:43:26,600 --> 01:43:30,920
want them to take away. Just put it there and 
tell them exactly what you want them to learn.

1144
01:43:30,920 --> 01:43:32,320
Yes. I love that.

1145
01:43:32,320 --> 01:43:38,040
