1202
01:48:57,880 --> 01:49:01,920
journey. I'm curious if there's a story 
from that experience that comes to mind  

1203
01:49:01,920 --> 01:49:07,680
that's like a wild part of that journey 
or something that might surprise people.

1204
01:49:09,280 --> 01:49:15,800
Well, the journey lasted almost seven months, 
and it was the craziest journey of my life. I  

1205
01:49:15,800 --> 01:49:25,600
went into that with no experience whatsoever 
speaking, so really just a random amateur,  

1206
01:49:25,600 --> 01:49:33,160
and I just climbed the ladder by outworking 
everybody. The story that came to mind right  

1207
01:49:33,160 --> 01:49:42,400
away was six days before the semifinals. So I'm 
six days before the semifinals and I've qualified  

1208
01:49:42,400 --> 01:49:48,480
for the semifinals two and a half months ago. So 
I'm nobody, now I'm going to the semifinals of  

1209
01:49:48,480 --> 01:49:53,800
the world championships of public speaking. 
So my mind really is struggling to compute,  

1210
01:49:53,800 --> 01:50:02,040
and I had finally unlocked a speech that I thought 
was worthy of giving on the final stage. You have  

1211
01:50:02,040 --> 01:50:06,200
to show up there for the semifinals with one 
speech, and then the next day, if ever you win,  

1212
01:50:06,200 --> 01:50:10,640
you're going to the finals and you have to 
have a brand new speech, a completely different  

1213
01:50:10,640 --> 01:50:15,840
speech that you're going to give on that stage.
So you need two speeches ready to go, and both of  

1214
01:50:15,840 --> 01:50:22,200
those speeches have to be in theory, world-class. 
I'm six days before. I was struggling at that,  

1215
01:50:22,200 --> 01:50:27,040
really, really struggling to get that speech 
together. I finally got something and Michael  

1216
01:50:27,040 --> 01:50:33,360
managed to get me. I was flying I think 
two days later to Vancouver for the semis,  

1217
01:50:33,360 --> 01:50:39,120
and Michael managed to unlock this one opportunity 
to speak in front of 50 people to give it a try.  

1218
01:50:39,120 --> 01:50:45,360
And so I ran there. I give the speech, and as 
usual, we film. I film every single speech.  

1219
01:50:45,360 --> 01:50:48,760
I gave more than a hundred speeches over 
seven months, and I filmed every single  

1220
01:50:48,760 --> 01:50:54,120
speech. And we'd get home, we'd ask everybody 
for feedback, and I get home and I'm thinking,  

1221
01:50:54,120 --> 01:51:01,720
"Man, something is wrong. Something is wrong." 
I was so pumped. I wept. I genuinely wept as I  

1222
01:51:01,720 --> 01:51:07,360
wrote the speech because it was so moving. 
It was all about my life. It was something  

1223
01:51:07,360 --> 01:51:12,080
that I was so connected to. I don't know, 
probably the emotion of the pressure as well,  

1224
01:51:12,080 --> 01:51:17,520
but that's how much I believed in that speech.
We get home, we put the speech on the computer,  

1225
01:51:17,520 --> 01:51:22,720
and as I get to the most important 
part of the speech, I see two things  

1226
01:51:22,720 --> 01:51:28,480
happen. So this is the moment where I'm 
expecting people to pull out their tissues.  

1227
01:51:28,480 --> 01:51:36,080
One person pulls up the agenda for the event 
that they're at and is starting to look at  

1228
01:51:36,080 --> 01:51:44,840
the agenda. Another person pulls out their phone, 
another person starts going through their purse,  

1229
01:51:44,840 --> 01:51:50,320
and I'm looking at this, and suddenly I realized, 
"Oh, this speech, nobody cares about this. This is  

1230
01:51:50,320 --> 01:51:53,520
not a good speech. This is terrible." And 
then I go through all of these feedbacks. 

1231
01:51:53,520 --> 01:51:59,600
I have 50 pieces of feedback, and all I'm getting 
is, "Good luck for the semi-finals. It's going  

1232
01:51:59,600 --> 01:52:05,400
to go great. I thought it was good", and I'm 
like, "I'm going to humiliate myself. This is  

1233
01:52:05,400 --> 01:52:15,560
terrible." So I had waves of anxiety. I threw my 
speech away, and in five days from the ground up,  

1234
01:52:15,560 --> 01:52:23,360
I rebuilt a completely new speech that was 
basically the best of everything I'd explored,  

1235
01:52:23,360 --> 01:52:27,880
everything I'd experimented with over the 
course of the three months leading up to that,  

1236
01:52:27,880 --> 01:52:34,000
the jokes that worked the best, like a stand-up 
comic would. I built my special and I focused on  

1237
01:52:34,000 --> 01:52:43,520
different areas like all of the transitions.
And right before the semi-finals, I gave the  

1238
01:52:43,520 --> 01:52:50,880
speech to one person. I was in Vancouver trying 
to internalize my speech and memorizing it in a  

1239
01:52:50,880 --> 01:52:57,120
plaza where I delimited the size of the stage 
and I'm just giving my speech out loud to get  

1240
01:52:57,120 --> 01:53:01,760
over the nerves, so I'm ready for the pressure to 
see if my brain will remember it and everything. 

1241
01:53:01,760 --> 01:53:07,600
Anyways, I gave it in front of one person who 
was our district director at Toastmasters,  

1242
01:53:07,600 --> 01:53:13,600
and this is a speech meant for 500 to a 
thousand people, not one person. So I was  

1243
01:53:13,600 --> 01:53:18,040
scared it would flop. But in the middle of the 
speech, which is a completely different one,  

1244
01:53:18,040 --> 01:53:25,040
I saw a tear roll down her cheek, and then she 
just hugged me and said, "You got it. You did it.  

1245
01:53:25,040 --> 01:53:32,200
You did it." I walked out on that stage and I made 
it, and I won the semi-finals with that speech. 

1246
01:53:32,200 --> 01:53:41,400
I think to me, that was really the, it showed 
me that everything I'd done was worth something,  

1247
01:53:41,400 --> 01:53:46,960
that it actually worked. If I was able to 
build a speech in five days, that could  

1248
01:53:46,960 --> 01:53:52,160
get me a win at the semi-finals of the world 
championships. That was kind of the ultimate,  

1249
01:53:52,160 --> 01:53:57,920
"Wow, I won." So when I walked into the 
finals, to me, I felt like I had already won.

1250
01:53:57,920 --> 01:54:04,960
Wow, that is a story. What an arc. Amazing. I'm 
so happy you asked that question. Now I just  

1251
01:54:04,960 --> 01:54:08,720
want to watch that speech and I want to learn more 
